<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I</emphasis>
anal plate 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">J</emphasis>
genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Abdomen</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Abdominal tergites I-VII with wrinkles, those distinctly developed on marginal area; tergite VIII with scaly sculptures, swollen into conical spinal process, with 7-10 long, thick, and blunt setae at margin (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figure 19. Aspidophorodon (Eoessigia) obtusirostre Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of head B antenna C ultimate rostral segment D marginal seta of abdominal tergite I E spinal seta of abdominal tergite VIII F spinal process of abdominal tergite VIII G siphunculus H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702354" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">19F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Aspidophorodon (Eoessigia) obtusirostre Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of body B dorsal view of head C antenna D ultimate rostral segment E hind tibia and tarsi F siphunculus G spinal process of abdominal tergite VIII H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702355" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">20G</figureCitation>
). Venter of abdominal tergites III-VIII with fine spinules arranged in rows. Dorsal setae of abdominal tergites I-VI short, thick, and blunt (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figure 19. Aspidophorodon (Eoessigia) obtusirostre Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of head B antenna C ultimate rostral segment D marginal seta of abdominal tergite I E spinal seta of abdominal tergite VIII F spinal process of abdominal tergite VIII G siphunculus H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702354" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">19D</figureCitation>
), tergite VII long, thick, and blunt, occasionally short, thick, and blunt, tergite VIII long, thick, and blunt with distinct setal tubercles (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figure 19. Aspidophorodon (Eoessigia) obtusirostre Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of head B antenna C ultimate rostral segment D marginal seta of abdominal tergite I E spinal seta of abdominal tergite VIII F spinal process of abdominal tergite VIII G siphunculus H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702354" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">19E</figureCitation>
); ventral setae short and pointed. Abdominal tergites I and II each with one pair of spinal, pleural, and marginal setae; tergites III-VII each with one pair of spinal and marginal setae. Spiracles reniform, open or closed; spiracular plates slightly swollen. SIPH long spoon-shaped, broad at base, thin at the middle, swollen distally, with developed imbrications, obliquely truncated at tip, without flange (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figure 19. Aspidophorodon (Eoessigia) obtusirostre Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of head B antenna C ultimate rostral segment D marginal seta of abdominal tergite I E spinal seta of abdominal tergite VIII F spinal process of abdominal tergite VIII G siphunculus H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702354" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">19G</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Aspidophorodon (Eoessigia) obtusirostre Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of body B dorsal view of head C antenna D ultimate rostral segment E hind tibia and tarsi F siphunculus G spinal process of abdominal tergite VIII H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702355" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">20F</figureCitation>
). Cauda long tongue-shaped, with spinulose imbrications, slightly constricted at base and weakly pointed at apex (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figure 19. Aspidophorodon (Eoessigia) obtusirostre Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of head B antenna C ultimate rostral segment D marginal seta of abdominal tergite I E spinal seta of abdominal tergite VIII F spinal process of abdominal tergite VIII G siphunculus H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702354" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">19H</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Aspidophorodon (Eoessigia) obtusirostre Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of body B dorsal view of head C antenna D ultimate rostral segment E hind tibia and tarsi F siphunculus G spinal process of abdominal tergite VIII H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702355" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">20H</figureCitation>
); with 6-11 setae, including two pairs of very long and pointed setae, 0.055-0.061mm and 2-7 short and pointed setae, 0.027-0.041mm. Anal plate semicircular, spinulose (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figure 19. Aspidophorodon (Eoessigia) obtusirostre Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of head B antenna C ultimate rostral segment D marginal seta of abdominal tergite I E spinal seta of abdominal tergite VIII F spinal process of abdominal tergite VIII G siphunculus H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702354" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">19I</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Aspidophorodon (Eoessigia) obtusirostre Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of body B dorsal view of head C antenna D ultimate rostral segment E hind tibia and tarsi F siphunculus G spinal process of abdominal tergite VIII H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702355" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">20I</figureCitation>
), with 8-13 setae. Genital plate transversely oval, with sparse spinules in transverse stripes (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figure 19. Aspidophorodon (Eoessigia) obtusirostre Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of head B antenna C ultimate rostral segment D marginal seta of abdominal tergite I E spinal seta of abdominal tergite VIII F spinal process of abdominal tergite VIII G siphunculus H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure19" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702354" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">19J</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Aspidophorodon (Eoessigia) obtusirostre Qiao &amp; Xu, sp. nov. Apterous viviparous female A dorsal view of body B dorsal view of head C antenna D ultimate rostral segment E hind tibia and tarsi F siphunculus G spinal process of abdominal tergite VIII H cauda I anal plate J genital plate. Scale bars: 0.10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1106.77912.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/702355" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">20J</figureCitation>
), with 4 or 5 anterior setae and 5-7 setae along the posterior margin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The new species is named for its short and blunt URS. The Latin word 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">obtus</emphasis>
means blunt, and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">rostre</emphasis>
for rostrum, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">obtusirostre</emphasis>
being the neuter form of the adjective.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="taxonomic notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Taxonomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The new species resembles 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. indicum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="indicum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. indicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(David, Rajasingh &amp; Narayanan) in median frontal tubercle protuberant, rectangular; dorsal setae of head between antennal tubercles thick and blunt; abdominal tergite VIII with conical spinal process; SIPH long spoon-shaped; but differs from it as follows: dorsum of head covered with wavy sculptures, those distinctly developed between compound eyes, thoracic nota and abdominal tergites I-VII with wavy sculptures (the latter: dorsum of head with densely semicircular and wavy sculptures, thoracic nota, and abdominal tergites I-VII with semicircular and wavy sculptures); antennae 5-segmented, 0.30-0.36 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as body length (the latter: antennae 6-segmented, 0.38-0.52 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as body length); URS short and blunt, 1.27-1.94 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as the basal width, 0.70-0.84 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as 2HT (the latter: URS long wedge-shaped, 2.06-2.54 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as the basal width, 0.89-1.10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as 2HT).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
